Every Spark job — no matter how big — comes down to three roles.

First, the driver. The driver runs your code, builds the execution plan, and decides what work to send out. Think of it as the project manager — it never lifts a box itself.

Second, the executors. These are the worker processes spread across the cluster. They hold your data partitions in memory and actually run the computations — the delivery drivers, each on their own route.

Third, the cluster manager. Its only job is to hand out machines to your app. It allocates resources, but it doesn't understand your job at all.

That's it: the driver plans, the executors do the work, and the cluster manager allocates the machines. Get those three straight and the rest of Spark clicks into place.

